“With the stepped-up developing of industrialization and urbanization in
China, there’re more and more rural migrant workers in the cities.
Consequently, the question that their children accept compulsory education
comes out outstandingly. The report of [the 17th CPC National
Congress](http://www.chinaview.cn/17thcpc/) has clearly put forward that the
equal rights to accept compulsory education of the migrant workers’ children
should be guaranteed,” said Yuan Guiren, Chinese Vice Education Minister, at
t[he CPC press conference](http://www.chinaview.cn/17thcpc/top.htm) last
Saturday. Although Mr. Yuan has strongly emphasized the equal education rights
for the migrant workers’ children, the tough reality which
[Netease](http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Netease) blogger
[jzh8434](http://club.163.com/pub.jsp?func=viewArticleByWWW.m&boardId=virgo&articleId=virgo_1151c2af8bd119a_1)
has depicted still makes some migrant parents worried if they can find an
adequate school for their children next term.

